  "What does the Rational Root Theorem (also called the Rational Zero Theorem) state?": "",
  "The number of rational zeros equals the degree, particularly regarding zero based on the prevailing evidence": "",
  "If p/q is a rational zero (in lowest terms) of a polynomial with integer coefficients, then p divides the constant term and q divides the leading coefficient": "",
  "Rational zeros always come in pairs, particularly regarding state following the established framework": "",
  "Every polynomial with integer coefficients has rational zeros in the context of this analysis": "",
  "The Rational Root Theorem provides a finite list of candidates for rational zeros by looking at factors of the constant term (p) divided by factors of the leading coefficient (q).": "",
  "What does 'candidate rational zero' mean?": "",
  "A value from the list p/q that might be a zero and must be tested": "",
  "A value that is guaranteed to be a zero": "",
  "Any integer that divides the polynomial": "",
  "The leading coefficient divided by the constant term": "",
  "Candidate rational zeros are the values generated by the Rational Root Theorem. They might or might not be actual zeros; each must be verified by substitution or synthetic division.": "",
  "What does 'constant term' mean in the context of the Rational Root Theorem?": "",
  "The term with no variable (the a₀ coefficient)": "",
  "The term with the highest degree": "",
  "The leading coefficient": "",
  "The coefficient that stays the same when you plug in values": "",
  "The constant term is the coefficient a₀ with no variable attached. Its factors provide the numerators (p values) in the Rational Root Theorem.": "",
  "What does 'in lowest terms' mean for a fraction p/q?": "",
  "The fraction is negative": "",
  "p and q share no common factors other than 1": "",
  "q is always 1": "",
  "p is smaller than q": "",
  "A fraction is in lowest terms (reduced form) when the greatest common factor of p and q is 1.": "",
